K-means Algorithm

Data clustering is one of the main mathematical applications variety of algorithms have been developed to tackle the problem. K-means is one of the basic algorithms for data clustering.

Prerequisites

The reader should be familiar with basic linear algebra.

Competences

The reader should be able to recognise applications where K-means algorithm can be efficiently used and use it.

Credits. The notebook was initially derived from M.Sc. Thesis of Ivančica Mirošević.

12.0 μs

Definitions

Data clustering problem is the following: partition the given set of m objects of the same type into k subsets according to some criterion. Additional request may be to find the optimal k.

K-means clustering problem is the following: partition the set X={x1,x2,⋯,xm} , where xi∈Rn, into k clusters π={C1,C2,...,Ck} such that

J(π)=∑i=1k∑x∈Ci∥x−ci∥22→min

over all possible partitions. Here ci=1|Ci|∑x∈Cix is the mean of points in Ci and |Ci| is the cardinality of Ci.

11.6 μs

K-means clustering algorithm

  1. Initialization: Choose initial set of k means {c1,…,ck} (for example, by choosing randomly k points from X).

  2. Assignment step: Assign each point x to one nearest mean ci.

  3. Update step: Compute the new means.

  4. Iteration: Repeat Steps 2 and 3 until the assignment no longer changes.

14.5 μs

First Variation clustering algorithm

A first variation of a partition π={C1,…,Ck} is a partition π′={C1′,⋯,Ck′} obtained by moving a single point x from a cluster Ci to a cluster Cj. Notice that π is a first variation of itself.

A next partition of the partition π is a partition next⁡(π)=argminπ′⁡J(π′).

We have the following algorithm:

  1. Choose initial partition π.

  2. Compute next⁡(π)

  3. If J(next⁡(π))<J(π), set π=next⁡(π) and go to Step 2

  4. Stop.

13.6 μs

Facts

  1. The k-means clustering problem is NP-hard.

  2. In the k-means algorithm, J(π) decreases in every iteration.

  3. K-means algorithm can converge to a local minimum.

  4. Each iteration of the k-means algorithm requires O(mnk) operations.

  5. K-means algorithm is implemented in the function kmeans() in the package Clustering.jl.

  6. J(π)=trace⁡(SW), where

SW=∑i=1k∑x∈Ci(x−ci)(x−ci)T=∑i=1k12|Ci|∑x∈Ci∑y∈Ci(x−y)(x−y)T.

Let c denote the mean of X. Then SW=ST−SB, where

ST=∑x∈X(x−c)(x−c)T=12m∑i=1m∑j=1m(xi−xj)(xi−xj)T,SB=∑i=1k|Ci|(ci−c)(ci−c)T=12m∑i=1k∑j=1k|Ci||Cj|(ci−cj)(ci−cj)T.

  1. In order to try to avoid convergence to local minima, the k-means algorithm can be enhanced with first variation by adding the following steps:

    1. Compute next⁡(π).

    2. If J(next⁡(π))<J(π), set π=next⁡(π) and go to Step 2.

1.7 s

What happens?

We see that the algorithm, although simple, for this example converges to a local minimum.

Let us try the function kmeans() from the package Clustering.jl. The inputs to kmeans() are:

  • a matrix whose columns are points,

  • number of clusters we are looking for, and,

  • optionally, the method to compute initial means.

If we choose init=:rand, the results are similar. If we choose init=:kmpp, which is the default, the results are better, but convergence to a local minimum is still possible.

Run the clustering several times!

seeding_algorithm(s::Symbol) = 
    s == :rand ? RandSeedAlg() :
    s == :kmpp ? KmppAlg() :
    s == :kmcen ? KmCentralityAlg() :
    error("Unknown seeding algorithm $s")

Concentric rings

The k-means algorithm works well if clusters can be separated by hyperplanes. In this example it is not the case.
